ground_truth_data.question_text: Which budget functions show the largest year-over-year increases?

    b1.fiscal_year,

    budget_outlays b1

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which industries show higher GDP growth rates than the national average?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
WITH national_gdp_growth AS (
    SELECT 
        (MAX(numeric_value) - MIN(numeric_value)) / MIN(numeric_value) * 100 AS national_growth_rate
    FROM 
        time_series_data
    WHERE 
        category = 'GDP' AND 
        numeric_value IS NOT NULL
),
industry_growth AS (
    SELECT 
        category AS industry,
        (MAX(numeric_value) - MIN(numeric_value)) / MIN(numeric_value) * 100 AS industry_growth_rate
    FROM 
        time_series_data
    WHERE 
        category != 'GDP' AND 
        numeric_value IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY 
        category
)
SELECT 
    industry, 
    industry_growth_rate
FROM 
    industry_growth, national_gdp_growth
WHERE 
    industry_growth_rate > national_growth_rate
ORDER BY 
    industry_growth_rate DESC
LIMIT 20;

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which industries contribute disproportionately to economic growth vs. their size?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
SELECT 
    tsd.category AS industry,
    SUM(tsd.numeric_value) AS total_gdp_contribution,
    bo.total_outlays,
    (SUM(tsd.numeric_value) / bo.total_outlays) AS contribution_ratio
FROM 
    time_series_data tsd
JOIN 
    (SELECT 
        function_name, 
        SUM(outlay_amount) AS total_outlays
     FROM 
        budget_outlays
     WHERE 
        function_name IS NOT NULL
     GROUP BY 
        function_name) bo
ON 
    tsd.category = bo.function_name
WHERE 
    tsd.category IS NOT NULL
    AND tsd.source = 'BEA'
GROUP BY 
    tsd.category, bo.total_outlays
HAVING 
    contribution_ratio > 1.0
ORDER BY 
    contribution_ratio DESC
LIMIT 20;

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which industries show correlated growth patterns?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
WITH IndustryGrowth AS (
    SELECT 
        industry_name, 
        year, 
        SUM(gdp_value) AS total_gdp
    FROM 
        industry_gdp
    WHERE 
        gdp_value IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY 
        industry_name, year
),
IndustryGrowthRate AS (
    SELECT 
        ig1.industry_name,
        ig1.year,
        (ig1.total_gdp - COALESCE(ig2.total_gdp, 0)) / COALESCE(ig2.total_gdp, 1) AS growth_rate
    FROM 
        IndustryGrowth ig1
    LEFT JOIN 
        IndustryGrowth ig2 ON ig1.industry_name = ig2.industry_name AND ig1.year = ig2.year + 1
)
SELECT 
    ig1.industry_name AS industry1,
    ig2.industry_name AS industry2,
    COUNT(*) AS correlated_years
FROM 
    IndustryGrowthRate ig1
JOIN 
    IndustryGrowthRate ig2 ON ig1.year = ig2.year AND ig1.industry_name < ig2.industry_name
WHERE 
    ABS(ig1.growth_rate - ig2.growth_rate) < 0.05
GROUP BY 
    ig1.industry_name, ig2.industry_name
HAVING 
    COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY 
    correlated_years DESC
LIMIT 10;

ground_truth_data.question_text: How are fiscal years aligned across different government datasets?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
SELECT 
    tsd.fiscal_calendar AS time_series_fiscal_calendar,
    bo.fiscal_year AS budget_outlays_fiscal_year,
    ig.year AS industry_gdp_fiscal_year,
    COUNT(DISTINCT tsd.record_id) AS time_series_count,
    COUNT(DISTINCT bo.record_id) AS budget_outlays_count,
    COUNT(DISTINCT ig.record_id) AS industry_gdp_count
FROM 
    time_series_data tsd
LEFT JOIN 
    budget_outlays bo ON tsd.fiscal_calendar = CAST(bo.fiscal_year AS TEXT)
LEFT JOIN 
    industry_gdp ig ON tsd.fiscal_calendar = CAST(ig.year AS TEXT)
WHERE 
    tsd.fiscal_calendar IS NOT NULL
    AND bo.fiscal_year IS NOT NULL
    AND ig.year IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY 
    tsd.fiscal_calendar, bo.fiscal_year, ig.year
ORDER BY 
    time_series_fiscal_calendar, budget_outlays_fiscal_year, industry_gdp_fiscal_year
LIMIT 100;

ground_truth_data.question_text: How do acceleration vs. deceleration patterns compare across indicators?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
WITH yearly_changes AS (
  SELECT 
    indicator_id,

    numeric_value,
    LAG(numeric_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) as prev_value,
    numeric_value - LAG(numeric_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) as change_value
  FROM time_series_data 
  WHERE numeric_value IS NOT NULL 
    AND period_type = 'annual'
),
acceleration_patterns AS (
  SELECT 
    indicator_id,
    year,
    change_value,
    LAG(change_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) as prev_change,
    CASE 
      WHEN change_value > LAG(change_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) THEN 'acceleration'
      WHEN change_value < LAG(change_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) THEN 'deceleration'
      ELSE 'stable'
    END as pattern_type
  FROM yearly_changes
  WHERE change_value IS NOT NULL
)
SELECT 
  indicator_id,
  pattern_type,
  COUNT(*) as pattern_count,
  ROUND(AVG(ABS(change_value - prev_change)), 2) as avg_pattern_magnitude,
  ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / SUM(COUNT(*)) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id), 1) as pattern_percentage
FROM acceleration_patterns
WHERE pattern_type IN ('acceleration', 'deceleration')
  AND prev_change IS NOT NULL;

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which transition patterns are reversible vs. irreversible?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
SELECT 
    t1.function_name,
    t1.fiscal_year as start_year,
    t2.fiscal_year as end_year,
    t1.outlay_amount as start_amount,
    t2.outlay_amount as end_amount,
    ((t2.outlay_amount - t1.outlay_amount) / t1.outlay_amount * 100) as change_percent,
    CASE 
        WHEN ABS((t2.outlay_amount - t1.outlay_amount) / t1.outlay_amount * 100) < 10 THEN 'Reversible'
        WHEN ((t2.outlay_amount - t1.outlay_amount) / t1.outlay_amount * 100) > 50 THEN 'Irreversible Growth'
        WHEN ((t2.outlay_amount - t1.outlay_amount) / t1.outlay_amount * 100) < -50 THEN 'Irreversible Decline'
        ELSE 'Potentially Reversible'
    END as transition_pattern

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which indicators show pro-cyclical vs. counter-cyclical patterns?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
WITH gdp_growth AS (
    SELECT 
        year, 
        (gdp_value - LAG(gdp_value) OVER (ORDER BY year)) / LAG(gdp_value) OVER (ORDER BY year) AS gdp_growth_rate
    FROM 
        industry_gdp
    WHERE 
        gdp_value IS NOT NULL
),
indicator_growth AS (
    SELECT 
        indicator_id, 
        year, 
        (numeric_value - LAG(numeric_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year)) / LAG(numeric_value) OVER (PARTITION BY indicator_id ORDER BY year) AS indicator_growth_rate
    FROM 
        time_series_data
    WHERE 
        numeric_value IS NOT NULL
),
correlation_analysis AS (
    SELECT 
        i.indicator_id,
        AVG(i.indicator_growth_rate * g.gdp_growth_rate) AS correlation_coefficient
    FROM 
        indicator_growth i
    JOIN 
        gdp_growth g ON i.year = g.year
    GROUP BY 
        i.indicator_id
)
SELECT 
    indicator_id,
    CASE 
        WHEN correlation_coefficient > 0 THEN 'Pro-cyclical'
        WHEN correlation_coefficient < 0 THEN 'Counter-cyclical'
        ELSE 'No clear pattern'
    END AS cycle_pattern
FROM 
    correlation_analysis
ORDER BY 
    correlation_coefficient DESC;

ground_truth_data.question_text: Which indicators show linear vs. nonlinear response patterns?
ground_truth_data.reference_sql:
WITH linear_patterns AS (
    SELECT 
        category,
        COUNT(*) AS data_points,
        SUM(numeric_value) AS total_value,
        AVG(numeric_value) AS avg_value,
        MIN(numeric_value) AS min_value,
        MAX(numeric_value) AS max_value
    FROM 
        time_series_data
    WHERE 
        numeric_value IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY 
        category
    HAVING 
        (MAX(numeric_value) - MIN(numeric_value)) / NULLIF(AVG(numeric_value), 0) < 0.1
),
nonlinear_patterns AS (
    SELECT 
        category,
        COUNT(*) AS data_points,
        SUM(numeric_value) AS total_value,
        AVG(numeric_value) AS avg_value,
        MIN(numeric_value) AS min_value,
        MAX(numeric_value) AS max_value
    FROM 
        time_series_data
    WHERE 
        numeric_value IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY 
        category
    HAVING 
        (MAX(numeric_value) - MIN(numeric_value)) / NULLIF(AVG(numeric_value), 0) >= 0.1
)
SELECT 
    'Linear' AS pattern_type,
    category,
    data_points,
    total_value,
    avg_value,
    min_value,
    max_value
FROM 
    linear_patterns
UNION ALL
SELECT 
    'Nonlinear' AS pattern_type,
    category,
    data_points,
    total_value,
    avg_value,
    min_value,
    max_value
FROM 
    nonlinear_patterns
ORDER BY 
    pattern_type ASC, data_points DESC
LIMIT 20;
